Part A: Clustering using K-means

The Iris dataset contains information about Iris Flowers, including measurements of their sepals and petals. The goal is to predict the species of iris based on the sepal and petal measurements.

It consists of 150 rows (samples) and 4 columns (variables).

VARIABLE DESCRIPTION:

  • Sepal Length: The length of the sepals, which are the outer parts of the flower that protect the petals when in bud

  • Sepal Width: The width of the sepals

  • Petal Length: The length of the petals, which are the colorful parts of the flower that attract pollinators

  • Petal Width: The width of the petals

  • Species: The species of iris flower. These three species: 0. Iris-setosa

    1. Iris-versicolor
    2. Iris-virginica

5. Elbow test to determine optimal number of clusters

In[213]:
Sum_of_squared_error = []
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans.fit(Iris_normalized)
    Sum_of_squared_error.append(kmeans.inertia_)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.scatter(range(1, 10), Sum_of_squared_error)
plt.plot(range(1, 10), Sum_of_squared_error)
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (K)')
plt.ylabel('Sum of squared error')
plt.title('Elbow Test')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

Part B: Association Rule Mining using Apriori

Online Retail Transactions containing items purchased by customers from an online retailer. The dataset contains a large number of transactions, making it suitable for analysis related to sales patterns, customer behavior, and inventory management.

It consists of 541909 rows (transactions) and 8 columns (variables).

VARIABLE DESCRIPTION:

  1. InvoiceNo: Unique identifer for each invoice
  2. StockCode: Unique identifer for each product
  3. Description: Name or description of the product
  4. Quantity: Number of Units Sold
  5. InvoiceDate: Date and Time of the transaction
  6. UnitPrice: Price per unit of the product
  7. CustomerID: Unique Identifier for each customer
  8. Country: Country where the customer is located

3. Using the apriori algorithm to generate association rules

In[373]:
# Use the apriori command to generate rules with minimal support , minimal confidence, and max length = 2.
OnlineRetailTransactions_rules = apriori(OnlineRetailTransactions, min_support = 0.017, min_confidence = 0.5, max_length=2)
OnlineRetailTransactions_rules = list(OnlineRetailTransactions_rules)
In[374]:
# Display all rules
all_rules = pd.DataFrame(columns=('LHS','RHS','support','confidence','lift'))
for i in range(len(OnlineRetailTransactions_rules)):
  for rule_ in OnlineRetailTransactions_rules[i].ordered_statistics:
    all_rules = pd.concat([all_rules, pd.DataFrame({'LHS':[','.join(list(rule_.items_base))],'RHS':[','.join(list(rule_.items_add))], 'support': [OnlineRetailTransactions_rules[i].support], 'confidence': [rule_.confidence], 'lift': [rule_.lift]})],ignore_index=True)

5. Interpretation of Each Rule

  1. Rule: pink regency teacup and saucer green regency teacup and saucer
    Support: 0.023320 (2.33% of transactions include both items)
    Confidence: 0.801061 (80% of transactions with pink teacup also have green teacup)
    Lift: 20.380629 (the likelihood of purchasing the green teacup is over 20 times higher when the pink teacup is purchased)
    Business Insight: This strong association suggests that customers who buy the pink regency teacup are very likely to also buy the green one, indicating a potential for cross-selling strategies or bundled promotions.

  2. Rule: pink regency teacup and saucer roses regency teacup and saucer
    Support: 0.021737 (2.17% of transactions include both items)
    Confidence: 0.746684 (75% of transactions with pink teacup also have roses teacup)
    Lift: 18.488647 (the likelihood of purchasing the roses teacup is nearly 18 times higher with the pink one)
    Business Insight: Similar to the first rule, this indicates a strong affinity between these two products, suggesting that marketing campaigns could highlight these items together, perhaps in themed collections.

  3. Rule: green regency teacup and saucer roses regency teacup and saucer
    Support: 0.028031 (2.80% of transactions include both items)
    Confidence: 0.713163 (71% of transactions with green teacup also have roses teacup)
    Lift: 17.658627 (the likelihood of purchasing the roses teacup is over 17 times higher when buying the green one)
    Business Insight: This rule reinforces the relationships among these products, indicating that customers may appreciate a broader selection of similar items, which could encourage retailers to create product bundles or promotional discounts.

  4. Rule: gardeners kneeling pad cup of tea gardeners kneeling pad keep calm
    Support: 0.019961 (1.996% of transactions include both items)
    Confidence: 0.697706 (70% of transactions with the kneeling pad cup also have the keep calm pad)
    Lift: 20.581527 (the likelihood of purchasing the keep calm pad is over 20 times higher when buying the cup)
    Business Insight: This suggests that customers interested in gardening-related products often purchase complementary items, indicating an opportunity for targeted marketing strategies aimed at gardening enthusiasts.

The Titanic dataset contains information about passengers aboard the Titanic, including their survival status and various attributes.

The dataset has 12 columns (variables) and 231 rows (passengers).

VARIABLE DESCRIPTION:

  1. PassengerId: Unique identifier for each passenger (1-231)
  2. Survived: Binary indicator of survival (0 = No, 1 = Yes)
  3. Pclass: Ticket class (1 = 1st, 2 = 2nd, 3 = 3rd)
  4. Name: Passenger's full name
  5. Sex: Passenger's gender (male or female)
  6. Age: Passenger's age in years (some values are missing)
  7. SibSp: Number of siblings/spouses aboard
  8. Parch: Number of parents/children aboard
  9. Ticket: Ticket number
  10. Fare: Passenger fare
  11. Cabin: Cabin number (many values are missing)
  12. Embarked: Port of embarkation (C = Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton)

TARGET variable : Survival

9. Conclusion

Model Performance Overview:
Decision Tree and Boosting Ensemble Models both achieved an accuracy of 0.76. This indicates that these models are effectively capturing the patterns in the dataset, likely due to their ability to handle non-linear relationships and interactions between features.
The Bagging Ensemble Model performed the best with an accuracy of 0.80, suggesting that aggregating predictions from multiple Decision Trees (via bagging) has enhanced the model's robustness and generalization capabilities.

Naive Bayes and Voting Ensemble Models:
The Naive Bayes Model achieved an accuracy of 0.68, which is lower than the other models. This model assumes feature independence, which may not hold true in this dataset, leading to its reduced performance.
The Voting Ensemble Model, which combines predictions from both the Decision Tree and Naive Bayes models, yielded an accuracy of 0.69. This score is slightly better than Naive Bayes alone but does not outperform the individual Decision Tree model.

Overall Assessment:
The results demonstrate that while simpler models like Naive Bayes can provide a baseline understanding of the data, more complex models (like Decision Trees and their ensembles) are necessary for achieving higher accuracy in predicting survival on the Titanic.
The findings emphasize the importance of model selection and evaluation in machine learning tasks, particularly in datasets with diverse features and potential interactions.

Conclusion
In summary, the accuracy scores from different models provide valuable insights into the factors influencing survival on the Titanic:

  1. Higher accuracy models indicate significant correlations between passenger characteristics (like class, gender, age, and family size) and survival likelihood.
  2. The results emphasize the importance of using robust modeling techniques to capture complex relationships within the data.

Overall, these findings highlight how socioeconomic factors and demographic characteristics played critical roles in determining who survived the Titanic disaster.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
